ive: Spinning Straw into Gold: Blond Hair and the Autobiographical Illusion in the Fiction of Esther Tusquets|title=Esther Tusquets: Scholarly Correspondences|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PsoxBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA75&q=blonde%20hair%20in%20northern%20European%20mythology%20and%20folklore|editor1-last=Molinaro|editor1-first=Nina L.|editor2-last=Pertusa-Seva|editor2-first=Inmaculada|location=Cambridge, England|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|isbn=978-1-4438-5908-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{citation|last=Stieber|first=Mary|date=2004|title=The Poetics of Appearance in the Attic Korai|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Poetics_of_Appearance_in_the_Attic_K.html?id=ERTMwHEkyvgC|location=Austin|publisher=University of Texas Press|isbn=9780292701809|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal| last = Thomas| first = Jeannie B.| year = 1997| title = Dumb Blondes, Dan Quayle, and Hillary Clinton: Gender, Sexuality, and Stupidity in Jokes | journal = The Journal of American Folklore| volume = 110| issue = 437| pages = 277\u2013313| doi = 10.2307/541162| jstor = 541162}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wiktionary|blond}}\n\n{{Commons category|Blond hair}}\n{{Commons category|Blond hair hair}}\n{{Commons category|Blond hair hair in art}}\n\n{{Hair colors}}\n\n[[Category:Blond hair| ]]\n[[Category:Hair color]]\n", "name_user": "Hunan201p", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAsia:corrected typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blond"}
{"title_page": "List of recreational vehicles", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=May 2018}}\n\nThis is a list various types of '''[[recreational vehicle]]s''' (RVs).\n\n[[File:Abenteuer Allrad 2013 - Unimog 437 U4000 6x6 RV Unicat MD52h.jpg|thumb|[[Unimog]] based [[Six-wheel drive|6x6]] [[overlanding]] capable [[Recreational vehicle|RV]]]]\n\n== Class A motorhome ==\n{{Main|Motorhome}}\n\n[[File:Busconversion.jpg|thumb|A typical [[luxury vehicle|luxury bus ]] conversion (Class A)]]\n\nConstructed on either a [[truck]]  chassis, a specially designed motor vehicle [[chassis]], or a commercial [[bus]] chassis, a Class A motorhome resembles a bus in design and has a flat or vertical front end with large side windows. ''[[Slideout]]''s on these vehicles may  allow for wider living areas when parked.\n\n=== Bus conversions ===\nA commercial [[bus|passenger bus]] that has been converted into an RV is a \u201cbus conversion\u201d.   Depending on the components added, such conversions are typically the largest motorhomes available.\n\n== Truck conversion motorhome ==\nThe term \"truck conversion\" has generally come to mean a heavy-duty truck (class 7/8 semi) chassis with a lengthened frame and living quarters built on. Advantages of a truck conversion over a standard Class A are safety, ease of service/maintenance, and usually a much higher power-to-weight ratio, since most semi-tractors are built to move a {{convert|80000|lb|adj=on}} combined weight. A disadvantage is that with the engine up front, they are louder than when the engine is in the back. They also tend to have a smaller interior than an equivalent-length Class A, since the engine/cab area does not contribute to the living quarters. Truck conversion motorhomes are most popular with the racing and horse community{{cn|date=January 2020}} since they are often much better suited to pulling heavy trailers than most other classes of motorhomes.\n\n== Class B motorhome (campervan) ==\n{{Main|Campervan}}\n[[File:TalbotAutoSleeper1991.jpg|thumb|right|200px|A small class B campervan]]\n\nBuilt using a conventional [[van]], to which either a raised roof has been added or the back replaced by a low-profile body (aka coach-built). In [[Australia]], a Class B motorhome is  distinct from a [[campervan]], as it is based on a large [[van]] that is, in turn, based on a truck. These motorhomes weigh up to 4,500&nbsp;kg and measure up to 6.4 m in length.\n\nMost Australian campervans are based on much smaller vehicles such as the [[Toyota HiAce]], while the middle ground is now populated by larger vans that blur the definition of campervan or motorhome. These include the [[Ford Transit]], [[Mercedes-Benz Sprinter]], [[Fiat Ducato]], and [[Iveco]].<ref>{{Cite news\n  | last =\n  | first =\n  | author-link =\n  | title = Feel at home on the road\n  | newspaper = The Courier-Mail\n  | location = Brisbane\n  | date = 19 June 2010\n  | accessdate =}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, Class B motorhomes are built on several different chassis depending on the motorhome manufacturer and engine design aims. Common chassis include the Mercedes Benz Sprinter diesel, the Dodge Ram Promaster gas, the Chevrolet Express gas, and the Ford Transit gas and diesel.\n\nIn the State of California, in order to qualify as Class B RV, a vehicle must have four of the following six '''built in''' items:\n#  a water system, typically a sink or shower\n# a refrigerator\n# a cooking system\n#  a fuel or 110\u00a0V electrical system\n# an AC unit or heater\n# a toilet\n{{fact|date=November 2017}}\n\n== Class C motorhome ==\n{{Main|Motorhome}}\n[[File:Class-C.jpg|thumb|right|200px|A Class C motorhome]]\nA Class C motorhome is built upon a minimal truck platform with a forward engine and transmission connected by [[driveshaft]] to a rear axle that propels dual-mounted rear wheels. Class C motorhomes are typically powered by [[gasoline]] (petrol) engines, although some have been converted to run on [[Propane#Motor fuel|propane]] (autogas) while others use [[diesel fuel|diesels]]. Transmissions are almost always [[automatic transmission|automatic]]. The original chassis is equipped from the truck factory to the coach builder with an attached forward cab section that is van or conventional truck based (known as a ''cutaway'' chassis). In North America, the [[Ford Motor Company#Trucks|Ford]] E350 or E450 chassis are the most typical in the 21st century, while in prior times the [[Dodge]]/[[Ram Trucks|Ram]] and [[Chevrolet]]/[[GMC (automobile)|GMC]] chassis were also used. Some smaller [[micro motorhomes]] were produced on Nissan and Toyota platforms from 1972\u20131994, [[Toyota Motorhomes]] continue to have a strong following. Some very large Class C motorhomes are based on even larger truck platforms, such as the Ford F650 and [[Freightliner Trucks|Freightliner]] XC chassis. In Europe, Ford and Fiat manufacture the majority of Class C motorhome chassis.\n\nThe rigid outer weatherproof superstructure of a Class C motorhome (attached onto the original cab and chassis) was typically constructed of a wooden frame covered by sheet metal, but in recent decades such materials as [[fibreglass]], plastics, composites, and lightweight metals have become the norm. With the introduction of ''slideout''s, the earlier design notion of increasing interior space by lengthening the entire motorhome (thus escalating the purchase price) gave way to new designs that offer increased width (albeit only possible in a completely stationary vehicle) while no longer requiring additional length.\n\nClass C motorhomes are characterized by a distinctive ''cab-over'' profile, containing either an upper sleeping area, a storage space, or a TV/entertainment section. In the [[UK]], the cab-over is known as a ''Luton peak'' or [[Luton body]]. A Class C motorhome is equipped with a kitchen/dining area featuring a refrigerator/freezer, a propane range (sometimes with an oven), a microwave oven, and a table with seating. It also has a lavatory with bath/shower, and has one or more sleeping areas as well as additional seating towards the front. An air conditioner, a water heater, a furnace, and an outside canopy are usually included. Optional equipment available at additional expense typically includes a generator set and roof-mounted solar power panels.\n\nA sub-category of Class C motorhomes is the ''toy hauler'', which combines a typical configuration with additional enclosed space aft dedicated to hauling dirt bikes, bicycles, [[All-terrain vehicle|ATVs]] or the like. Class C motorhomes often feature a towing hitch enabling the pulling of a light weight trailer such as for boats, or of a small car or truck. Class C motorhomes may also be referred to in some places as ''mini-motorhomes''. [https://www.lomondmotorhomehire.co.uk/ Touring outer hebrides motorhome]\n\n== Truck camper ==\n{{Main|Truck camper}}\n\n[[File:Camper - Kallonis Bay.jpg|thumb|left|200px|A truck camper]]\n\nA [[truck camper]] is a living space unit that is temporarily mounted into the bed of a [[pickup truck]] and secured against any tipping or wobbling while the truck is in motion. Great care must be taken in matching the weight and center balance point of the truck camper with the capabilities of the pickup truck itself in order to maintain safe handling of the vehicle while driving. Truck campers are much favored by those who do not wish to own a motorhome or trailer for only part-time use when the need for a truck is otherwise present.\n\nCommon uses are for backwoods travel, hunting, fishing, and particularly in North America on four wheel drive vehicles for off-roading or via rough roads to campsites. The smallest of truck campers provide a sleeping area with perhaps an ice box and storage cabinetry, while top-of-the-line campers feature a refrigerator/freezer, propane range/oven, microwave oven, air conditioner, furnace, water heater, and lavatory with shower. With the introduction of slideouts, the earlier design notion of increasing interior space by lengthening the entire camper (thus escalating the purchase price) gave way to new designs that offer increased width (albeit only possible in a completely stationary vehicle) while no longer requiring additional length.\n\nTypical North American consumer grade pickup trucks used for hauling full size slideout-equipped campers are of the Chevrolet/GMC 2500 through 3500 range, the Ram 2500 through 3500 range, and the Ford F-250 through 350 range, usually with long box bed lengths and sometimes with dual-mounted rear tires for the heaviest camper models.\n\n== Popup camper ==\n{{Main|Popup camper}}\n\n[[File:JaycoPopupCamper-2009-11-17.jpg|thumb|right|200px|A popup camper (a.k.a. ''tent trailer'')]]\n\nAlso known as a ''folding trailer'', ''tent camper'', ''tent trailer'', or ''camper trailer'', a popup trailer is a light-weight unit with pull-out bunks and tent walls that collapse for towing and for non-use storage. These campers are suitable for towing by most vehicles.{{cn|date=April 2019}}\n\n== Travel trailer ==\n{{Main|Travel trailer}}\nA unit with rigid sides designed to be towed, usually by a pickup truck, SUV, or minivan, with a bumper or frame hitch. In Britain they are known as ''caravans''. Bumper pull travel trailers like these range from 19' to 34' long.  They are  typically pulled by a large SUV or light to medium pickup truck (Class 2, 3 or 4).  Bumper pull travel trailers have between 1 and 4 axles.\n\n[[File:Caravan.jpg|thumb|left|200px|A European caravan]]\n\n== Teardrop trailer ==\n{{Main|Teardrop trailer}}\nA compact, lightweight travel trailer that resembles a large teardrop, sometimes seen being towed by [[motorcycles]].\n\n[[File:My teardrop.jpg|thumb|left|200px|A Teardrop Trailer]]\n\n== Hybrid trailer ==\nA blend between a travel trailer and a folding (tent) trailer. One type has rigid sides and pull-out tent sections (usually beds) while another type's top section of walls and its roof can be lowered over its bottom section to reduce its height for towing.\n\n[[File:KZHybridTrailer-2009-12-08.JPG|thumb|right|200px|A hybrid travel trailer]]\n\n== Fifth-wheel trailer ==\n\n[[File:Fifth-wheel.jpg|thumb|left|200px|A fifth-wheel trailer]]\n\nDesigned to be towed by a pickup or medium duty truck equipped with a special in-box hitch called a [[fifth wheel coupling]]. Part of the trailer body extends over the truck bed, shortening the total length of the vehicle and trailer combined. Some larger fifth-wheel trailers, usually over 40 feet (12.2 m) in length and 18,000 pounds (8,200&nbsp;kg) in weight, are  pulled by semi-trucks. Fifth-wheel trailers have become increasingly popular since they first became commercially available in the late 1960s. For some pickup truck owners the downside of a fifth-wheel trailer versus a conventional frame-hitch-mount travel trailer is that the former takes up space inside the truck cargo bed.\n\n== Park model (vacation/resort cottage) ==\nThis is a larger travel trailer \u2013 35 to 45 feet long \u2013 that is not self-contained. It is designed for park camping only; and while it is easily moved from site to site as a normal trailer is, it is not capable of \"dry camping\" as it does not have any water storage tanks and must be used with hookups.\n\n== Skoolie ==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Skoolie.jpg|thumb|A former school bus that has been converted into a RV.]] -->\nA former [[school bus]] or shuttle bus that has been converted into a RV.  This includes full size buses based on a dedicated school bus chassis, or a \"short bus\", based on a [[Cutaway van chassis|cutaway van]], heavy duty [[pickup truck]] cutaway, or medium duty truck cutaway with a bus body attached.  (A cutaway is where a vehicle frame is fitted with only a cab, motor, transmission, and tires.  A secondary manufacturer is responsible to fit additional body components.)    These are usually highly customized and done by their owners.  These can be done simply and inexpensively, or elaborately and expensive.  Full size buses are generally fall into the Class A rating, and the short buses fall into the Class C rating.  There are varying regulations in different states in the United States that affect the conversion of a school bus.  Some states, such as California and Illinois, require that the bus's signaling equipment (stop sign, flashing lights, etc.) be removed and the [[school bus yellow]] paint scheme be changed. Other states simply require that the \"School Bus\" signage at the top front and rear be removed.  Also, what needs to be installed prior to it being retitled from a bus to a RV varies from state to state.  Generally a bed, stove or oven, water tanks, toilet facilities, sinks, etc must be mounted to the vehicle. Along with that, skoolies are generally a cheaper option but also a vehicle that has the right necessities for one.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Recreational Vehicle}}\n[[Category:Recreational vehicles| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=May 2018}}\n\nThis is a list various types of '''[[recreational vehicle]]s''' (RVs).\n\n[[File:Abenteuer Allrad 2013 - Unimog 437 U4000 6x6 RV Unicat MD52h.jpg|thumb|[[Unimog]] based [[Six-wheel drive|6x6]] [[overlanding]] capable [[Recreational vehicle|RV]]]]\n\n== Class A motorhome ==\n{{Main|Motorhome}}\n\n[[File:Busconversion.jpg|thumb|A typical [[luxury vehicle|luxury bus ]] conversion (Class A)]]\n\nConstructed on either a [[truck]]  chassis, a specially designed motor vehicle [[chassis]], or a commercial [[bus]] chassis, a Class A motorhome resembles a bus in design and has a flat or vertical front end with large side windows. ''[[Slideout]]''s on these vehicles may  allow for wider living areas when parked.\n\n=== Bus conversions ===\nA commercial [[bus|passenger bus]] that has been converted into an RV is a \u201cbus conversion\u201d.   Depending on the components added, such conversions are typically the largest motorhomes available.\n\n== Truck conversion motorhome ==\nThe term \"truck conversion\" has generally come to mean a heavy-duty truck (class 7/8 semi) chassis with a lengthened frame and living quarters built on. Advantages of a truck conversion over a standard Class A are safety, ease of service/maintenance, and usually a much higher power-to-weight ratio, since most semi-tractors are built to move a {{convert|80000|lb|adj=on}} combined weight. A disadvantage is that with the engine up front, they are louder than when the engine is in the back. They also tend to have a smaller interior than an equivalent-length Class A, since the engine/cab area does not contribute to the living quarters. Truck conversion motorhomes are most popular with the racing and horse community{{cn|date=January 2020}} since they are often much better suited to pulling heavy trailers than most other classes of motorhomes.\n\n== Class B motorhome (campervan) ==\n{{Main|Campervan}}\n[[File:TalbotAutoSleeper1991.jpg|thumb|right|200px|A small class B campervan]]\n\nBuilt using a conventional [[van]], to which either a raised roof has been added or the back replaced by a low-profile body (aka coach-built). In [[Australia]], a Class B motorhome is  distinct from a [[campervan]], as it is based on a large [[van]] that is, in turn, based on a truck. These motorhomes weigh up to 4,500&nbsp;kg and measure up to 6.4 m in length.\n\nMost Australian campervans are based on much smaller vehicles such as the [[Toyota HiAce]], while the middle ground is now populated by larger vans that blur the definition of campervan or motorhome. These include the [[Ford Transit]], [[Mercedes-Benz Sprinter]], [[Fiat Ducato]], and [[Iveco]].<ref>{{Cite news\n  | last =\n  | first =\n  | author-link =\n  | title = Feel at home on the road\n  | newspaper = The Courier-Mail\n  | location = Brisbane\n  | date = 19 June 2010\n  | accessdate =}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, Class B motorhomes are built on several different chassis depending on the motorhome manufacturer and engine design aims. Common chassis include the Mercedes Benz Sprinter diesel, the Dodge Ram Promaster gas, the Chevrolet Express gas, and the Ford Transit gas and diesel.\n\nIn the State of California, in order to qualify as Class B RV, a vehicle must have four of the following six '''built in''' items:\n#  a water system, typically a sink or shower\n# a refrigerator\n# a cooking system\n#  a fuel or 110\u00a0V electrical system\n# an AC unit or heater\n# a toilet\n{{fact|date=November 2017}}\n\n== Class C motorhome ==\n{{Main|Motorhome}}\n[[File:Class-C.jpg|thumb|right|200px|A Class C motorhome]]\nA Class C motorhome is built upon a minimal truck platform with a forward engine and transmission connected by [[driveshaft]] to a rear axle that propels dual-mounted rear wheels. Class C motorhomes are typically powered by [[gasoline]] (petrol) engines, although some have been converted to run on [[Propane#Motor fuel|propane]] (autogas) while others use [[diesel fuel|diesels]]. Transmissions are almost always [[automatic transmission|automatic]]. The original chassis is equipped from the truck factory to the coach builder with an attached forward cab section that is van or conventional truck based (known as a ''cutaway'' chassis). In North America, the [[Ford Motor Company#Trucks|Ford]] E350 or E450 chassis are the most typical in the 21st century, while in prior times the [[Dodge]]/[[Ram Trucks|Ram]] and [[Chevrolet]]/[[GMC (automobile)|GMC]] chassis were also used. Some smaller [[micro motorhomes]] were produced on Nissan and Toyota platforms from 1972\u20131994, [[Toyota Motorhomes]] continue to have a strong following. Some very large Class C motorhomes are based on even larger truck platforms, such as the Ford F650 and [[Freightliner Trucks|Freightliner]] XC chassis. In Europe, Ford and Fiat manufacture the majority of Class C motorhome chassis.\n\nThe rigid outer weatherproof superstructure of a Class C motorhome (attached onto the original cab and chassis) was typically constructed of a wooden frame covered by sheet metal, but in recent decades such materials as [[fibreglass]], plastics, composites, and lightweight metals have become the norm. With the introduction of ''slideout''s, the earlier design notion of increasing interior space by lengthening the entire motorhome (thus escalating the purchase price) gave way to new designs that offer increased width (albeit only possible in a completely stationary vehicle) while no longer requiring additional length.\n\nClass C motorhomes are characterized by a distinctive ''cab-over'' profile, containing either an upper sleeping area, a storage space, or a TV/entertainment section. In the [[UK]], the cab-over is known as a ''Luton peak'' or [[Luton body]]. A Class C motorhome is equipped with a kitchen/dining area featuring a refrigerator/freezer, a propane range (sometimes with an oven), a microwave oven, and a table with seating. It also has a lavatory with bath/shower, and has one or more sleeping areas as well as additional seating towards the front. An air conditioner, a water heater, a furnace, and an outside canopy are usually included. Optional equipment available at additional expense typically includes a generator set and roof-mounted solar power panels.\n\nA sub-category of Class C motorhomes is the ''toy hauler'', which combines a typical configuration with additional enclosed space aft dedicated to hauling dirt bikes, bicycles, [[All-terrain vehicle|ATVs]] or the like. Class C motorhomes often feature a towing hitch enabling the pulling of a light weight trailer such as for boats, or of a small car or truck. Class C motorhomes may also be referred to in some places as ''mini-motorhomes''. [https://www.lomondmotorhomehire.co.uk/ Touring outer hebrides motorhome]\n\n== Truck camper ==\n{{Main|Truck camper}}\n\n[[File:Camper - Kallonis Bay.jpg|thumb|left|200px|A truck camper]]\n\nA [[truck camper]] is a living space unit that is temporarily mounted into the bed of a [[pickup truck]] and secured against any tipping or wobbling while the truck is in motion. Great care must be taken in matching the weight and center balance point of the truck camper with the capabilities of the pickup truck itself in order to maintain safe handling of the vehicle while driving. Truck campers are much favored by those who do not wish to own a motorhome or trailer for only part-time use when the need for a truck is otherwise present.\n\nCommon uses are for backwoods travel, hunting, fishing, and particularly in North America on four wheel drive vehicles for off-roading or via rough roads to campsites. The smallest of truck campers provide a sleeping area with perhaps an ice box and storage cabinetry, while top-of-the-line campers feature a refrigerator/freezer, propane range/oven, microwave oven, air conditioner, furnace, water heater, and lavatory with shower. With the introduction of slideouts, the earlier design notion of increasing interior space by lengthening the entire camper (thus escalating the purchase price) gave way to new designs that offer increased width (albeit only possible in a completely stationary vehicle) while no longer requiring additional length.\n\nTypical North American consumer grade pickup trucks used for hauling full size slideout-equipped campers are of the Chevrolet/GMC 2500 through 3500 range, the Ram 2500 through 3500 range, and the Ford F-250 through 350 range, usually with long box bed lengths and sometimes with dual-mounted rear tires for the heaviest camper models.\n\n== Popup camper ==\n{{Main|Popup camper}}\n\n[[File:JaycoPopupCamper-2009-11-17.jpg|thumb|right|200px|A popup camper (a.k.a. ''tent trailer'')]]\n\nAlso known as a ''folding trailer'', ''tent camper'', ''tent trailer'', or ''camper trailer'', a popup trailer is a light-weight unit with pull-out bunks and tent walls that collapse for towing and for non-use storage. These campers are suitable for towing by most vehicles.{{cn|date=April 2019}}\n\n== Travel trailer ==\n{{Main|Travel trailer}}\nA unit with rigid sides designed to be towed, usually by a pickup truck, SUV, or minivan, with a bumper or frame hitch. In Britain they are known as ''caravans''. Bumper pull travel trailers like these range from 19' to 34' long.  They are  typically pulled by a large SUV or light to medium pickup truck (Class 2, 3 or 4).  Bumper pull travel trailers have between 1 and 4 axles.\n\n[[File:Caravan.jpg|thumb|left|200px|A European caravan]]\n\n== Teardrop trailer ==\n{{Main|Teardrop trailer}}\nA compact, lightweight travel trailer that resembles a large teardrop, sometimes seen being towed by [[motorcycles]].\n\n[[File:My teardrop.jpg|thumb|left|200px|A Teardrop Trailer]]\n\n== Hybrid trailer ==\nA blend between a travel trailer and a folding (tent) trailer. One type has rigid sides and pull-out tent sections (usually beds) while another type's top section of walls and its roof can be lowered over its bottom section to reduce its height for towing.\n\n[[File:KZHybridTrailer-2009-12-08.JPG|thumb|right|200px|A hybrid travel trailer]]\n\n== Fifth-wheel trailer ==\n\n[[File:Fifth-wheel.jpg|thumb|left|200px|A fifth-wheel trailer]]\n\nDesigned to be towed by a pickup or medium duty truck equipped with a special in-box hitch called a [[fifth wheel coupling]]. Part of the trailer body extends over the truck bed, shortening the total length of the vehicle and trailer combined. Some larger fifth-wheel trailers, usually over 40 feet (12.2 m) in length and 18,000 pounds (8,200&nbsp;kg) in weight, are  pulled by semi-trucks. Fifth-wheel trailers have become increasingly popular since they first became commercially available in the late 1960s. For some pickup truck owners the downside of a fifth-wheel trailer versus a conventional frame-hitch-mount travel trailer is that the former takes up space inside the truck cargo bed.\n\n== Park model (vacation/resort cottage) ==\nThis is a larger travel trailer \u2013 35 to 45 feet long \u2013 that is not self-contained. It is designed for park camping only; and while it is easily moved from site to site as a normal trailer is, it is not capable of \"dry camping\" as it does not have any water storage tanks and must be used with hookups.\n\n== Skoolie ==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Skoolie.jpg|thumb|A former school bus that has been converted into a RV.]] -->\nA former [[school bus]] or shuttle bus that has been converted into a RV.  This includes full size buses based on a dedicated school bus chassis, or a \"short bus\", based on a [[Cutaway van chassis|cutaway van]], heavy duty [[pickup truck]] cutaway, or medium duty truck cutaway with a bus body attached.  (A cutaway is where a vehicle frame is fitted with only a cab, motor, transmission, and tires.  A secondary manufacturer is responsible to fit additional body components.)    These are usually highly customized and done by their owners.  These can be done simply and inexpensively, or elaborately and expensive.  Full size buses are generally fall into the Class A rating, and the short buses fall into the Class C rating.  There are varying regulations in different states in the United States that affect the conversion of a school bus.  Some states, such as California and Illinois, require that the bus's signaling equipment (stop sign, flashing lights, etc.) be removed and the [[school bus yellow]] paint scheme be changed. Other states simply require that the \"School Bus\" signage at the top front and rear be removed.  Also, what needs to be installed prior to it being retitled from a bus to a RV varies from state to state.  Generally a bed, stove or oven, water tanks, toilet facilities, sinks, etc must be mounted to the vehicle. Along with that, skoolies are generally a cheaper option but also a vehicle that has the the right necessities for one.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Recreational Vehicle}}\n[[Category:Recreational vehicles| ]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_recreational_vehicles"}
{"title_page": "Oh My God ((G)I-dle song)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Oh My God\n| cover      = \n| alt        = \n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[(G)I-dle]]\n| album      = [[I Trust]]\n| released   = April 6, 2020\n| format     = {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| recorded   = 2020\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[K-pop]]|[[Hip hop music|hip hop]]}}\n| length     = 3:15\n| label      = [[Cube Entertainment|Cube]]\n|writer=| producer   =  {{flatlist|\n* [[Jeon So-yeon|Soyeon]]\n* [[Cube Entertainment#In-house and guest composers|Yummy Tone]]\n* Simon Hong<ref>{{cite web|title= I Trust / (G)I-dle \u2013 TIDAL |url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/135852786/credits|publisher=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>}}\n| prev_title = [[Lion ((G)I-dle song) |Lion]]\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| next_title = \n| next_year  =\n| misc         = {{External music video\n | type        = single\n | header      = Music video\n | 1           = {{YouTube| om3n2ni8luE |\"Oh my god\"}}\n}}}}\n\n\"'''Oh My God'''\" (stylized as \"'''Oh my god'''\") is a song recorded by South Korean girl group [[(G)I-dle]] as the lead single for their third extended play ''[[I Trust]]''. It was released in Korean and English through [[Cube Entertainment|Cube]] on April 6, 2020. It was composed by [[Jeon So-yeon|Soyeon]] and long-time collaborator [[Cube Entertainment#In-house and guest composers|Yummy Tone]], while the lyrics for the English version were translated by Lauren Kaori.\n\n==Background==\n\"Oh My God\" was released in Korean and English language. According to [[Cho Mi-yeon|Miyeon]], they included the English version specially for global fans for the now-postponed ''I-Land: Who Am I Tour''.<ref name=\"celev\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theceluv.com/article.php?aid=1586162596316145007|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, '\ub2f9\ub2f9\ud568'\uc73c\ub85c 9\uac1c\uc6d4 \ub9cc\uc5d0 \ucef4\ubc31\u2026\"\ub450 \uac00\uc9c0 \ubc84\uc804 \ubb34\ub300 \uae30\ub300\"[\uc885\ud569]|work=The Celebrity News|author=Kim He-seo|date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n\"Oh My God\" was written and co-produced by leader [[Jeon So-yeon|Soyeon]], who composed the group's popular songs from \"[[Latata]]\" to \"[[Lion ((G)I-dle song) |Lion]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joynews24.com/view/1254174|title=\ucef4\ubc31' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ud0c0\uc774\ud2c0\uace1\uc740 '\uc624 \ub9c8\uc774 \uac13'\u2026'\ubbff\ub4e3' \uc804\uc18c\uc5f0 \uc790\uc791\uace1|trans-title=(G)I-dle the title song is 'Oh My God'\u2026 'Believe in' Jeon So-yeon's own composition|work=Joy News24|author= Jung Ji-won |date=March 31, 2020|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> It is composed in the key of [[E minor]], with a tempo of 110 [[beats per minute|BPM]] running 3:15 minutes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://musicstax.com/track/oh-my-god/2DmRXiyn03tOqKgEJXlaiJ|title=Key and BPM of Oh my god by (G)I-dle|website=musicstax.com|language=en-US|date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The song was conceptualized around the theme of 'self-trust' when encountering reality and experiencing feelings of rejection, confusion, recognition, and dignity. It is an urban hip hop track in which the stark differences in rhythm that correspond to the atmospheric changes within the song stand out. The fantasy-like mood and bold production are led by a vintage piano sound and strong 808 bass.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hanteonews.com/ko/article/all?fc=5227|title=[\uc2e0\ubcf4] 'I trust'\ub85c \ub3cc\uc544\uc628 (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, 'Oh my god' \uc18c\ub9ac \uc808\ub85c \ub098\uc624\ub294 \ucf58\uc149\ud2b8! \"\uc774\ubc88\uc5d0\ub3c4 \ubbff\uace0 \ub4e3\uc790!\"|trans-title=(G)I-dle returning to 'I trust', the concept of 'Oh my god' sound section! \"Let's believe and listen again!\"|work=Hanteo News|author=Kim Tae-young |date=April 3, 2020|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\"celev\"/> The song is dark, with lyrics that riff on contrasts \u2014 light and dark, purity and sin \u2014 to communicate the idea that true divinity comes from knowing and trusting yourself.<ref name=\"mtv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3162473/gi-dle-interview-oh-my-god-soyeon-i-trust/|title=RISING STARS (G)I-DLE ARE DEFINING THEIR OWN GENRE|work=[[MTV]]|author=Crystal Bell|date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box\n |quote=\"I didn't want to limit that 'she' to a certain being or a certain definition, so it's open to anything. I believe that all kinds of love are valuable and must be respected. That's why I don't want to limit 'she' to something specific.\"\n |source = \u2014 Soyeon talking about using 'She' in \"Oh My God\".<ref name=\"mtv\"/>\n |width= 35%\n |align= right\n}}\n\nThe specific lyrics \"Oh my god / she took me to the sky / Oh my god / she showed me all the stars\" sparked listeners questioning as to whom is being referred to. Soyeon responded that the imagery and lyrics represent love in many forms, and that she will leave it to the listener to interpret it their own way.<ref name=\"mtv\"/> \n\nThe song is written in [[Point-of-view shot|third person]] because it symbolises the detachment of ones improved present self from their lackluster past self to show that they are now a better person.\n\n==Music video==\n[[File:(G)I-dle - Oh My God.png|thumbnail|(G)I-dle in \"Oh My God\" music video.]]\nBefore its release, the song was accompanied by a music video teaser released midnight [[Time in South Korea|KST]] on April 6, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hankyung.com/entertainment/article/202004068059I|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ubbf8\ub2c8 3\uc9d1 \ud0c0\uc774\ud2c0\uace1 'Oh my god' \ubba4\uc9c1\ube44\ub514\uc624 \ud2f0\uc800 \uacf5\uac1c|trans-title=(G)I-dle 3rd mini album song 'Oh my god' music video teaser released|work=Hankyung|author=Lee Jun-hyung |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> The teaser exceeded 1 million views on YouTube in 11 hours.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news1.kr/articles/?3897898|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 '\uc624 \ub9c8\uc774 \uac13' MV \ud2f0\uc800, \uacf5\uac1c 11\uc2dc\uac04 \ub9cc\uc5d0 100\ub9cc \ubdf0 \ub3cc\ud30c|trans-title=(G)I-dle 'Oh My God' MV teaser breaks 1 million views in 11 hours|work=News1|author=Kim Min-ji|date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe music video opens with a solo dance by leader Soyeon in a white room which leads her to escape the reality and gradually spread into a dream.<ref name=\"MV\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tvreport.co.kr/2037849|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ubbff\uc74c\u2192\ub2f9\ub2f9\ud568...\ud30c\uaca9X\ubabd\ud658 'Oh my god' [\uccab\u97f3\uc0c1]|work=Tv Report|author= Park Hyun-min |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>. It contains dark visual elements such as scene that portrays confusion in ego with whole body soaked in purple liquid and red mud, black coloured body painting and pouring red liquid over ones face.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cubeent.co.kr/gidlealbum/4231703|title=(G)IDLE - I Trust album infomation|publisher=Cube Entertainment|date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> Towards the end of the video, Soojin whispers \"Ab imo pectore\" meaning 'from the bottom of my heart' or 'with deepest affection' in Latin.\n\nChoreography for the song was created by Star System while being directed by director Yoon Rima and Jang Dongju of Rigend Film production team.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.instagram.com/tv/B-ouPyMDXJW/?igshid=8bw0lb9pcpnj|title=starsystem_kor (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 [OH MY GOD] M/V|website=[[Instagram]]|date=6 April 2020}}</ref> The assistant directors were Lee Yongoh, Kim Eunah, Lee Sunhyu, Choi Eunjeong and Koo Eunji. Other key personnel were production assistant Choi Seongjin, Park Sangcheol and Il Joo while the Character Generator was Kim Eunah, Lee Sunhyu, Choi Eunjeong and Koo Eunji, Kim Bo-hyeong, Lee Yerim and Bae Haeun. The Director of Photography were Yun Inmo (ATOD), Park Junhee as the Gaffer and Shin Gwiock (A:WE) as the Art Director.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://vimeo.com/404530807|title=(G)IDLE - OH MY GOD MV|author=RIGEND FILM STUDIO|publisher=Vimeo|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA monotone lyric video for the song was released on April 8, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.donga.com/article/all/20200409/100576451/1|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \u2018Oh my god\u2019 \ub9ac\ub9ad \ube44\ub514\uc624 \uacf5\uac1c|date=April 9, 2020|publisher=Sports Donga|first=Jeon|last=Hyo-jin}}</ref>\n\n===Reception===\nMia Nazarena of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' was positive in an article about the album, praising the \"dramatic scenes with visually stunning sets, finely-tuned choreography, and carefully curated costume changes\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/9352173/g-i-dle-oh-my-god-video-i-trust-ep|title='Oh My God': (G)I-DLE Is Back With a New EP and Stunning Video|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|author=Mia Nazarena|date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 7, 2020, it was announced that the music video amassed 17 million views within 24 hours of release.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.xportsnews.com/?ac=article_view&entry_id=1255695|title=\"\ub610 \ub300\ubc15\" (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, 'Oh my god' MV 18\uc2dc\uac04\ub9cc\uc5d0 1200\ub9cc\ubdf0 \ub3cc\ud30c|trans-title=\n\"Another jackpot\" (G)I-dle, 'Oh my god' MV surpasses 12 million views in 18 hours|publisher=XSPortsNews|author=Jeon A-ram|date=April 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.g-enews.com/ko-kr/news/article/news_all/202004081105565115c4c55f9b3d_1/article.html?md=20200408112310_R#linkpop|title=[\uae00\ub85c\ubc8c-\uc5d4\ud130 24] (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, '\uc544\uc774 \ud2b8\ub7ec\uc2a4\ud2b8(I trust)' \uc544\uc774\ud2a0\uc988 \ud1b1\uc568\ubc94 35\uac1c \uc9c0\uc5ed 1\uc704|trans-title=[Global-Enter 24] (G)I-dle Ranked #1 in iTunes' Top 35 Albums of 'I Trust'|publisher=Global Economic|author=Kim Seong|date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The video broke (G)I-dle's personal record set in 2019 with the \"Lion\" music video, which garnered 5 million views in two days of its release,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportsworldi.com/newsView/20191105512364|title=\u2018\uc798 \ub098\uac00\ub294\u2019 (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \u2018LION' MV \u2018500\ub9cc \ubdf0 \ub3cc\ud30c\u2019|trans-title='Excellent' (G)I-dle, 'LION' MV 'Break through 5 million views'|publisher=Sports World|author=Jung Ga-young|date=November 5, 2019|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> It is also the first most viewed Kpop music videos in the first 24 hours by a girl group (fifth overall behind [[BTS]]'s \"[[Black Swan (song)|Black Swan]]\") on [[Youtube]] at that time. The record previously held by [[Everglow (group)|Everglow]]'s \"[[Reminiscence (EP)|Dun Dun]]\" with 16 million views.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pop.heraldcorp.com/view.php?ud=202002042148029652360_1|title=\uc5d0\ubc84\uae00\ub85c\uc6b0 '\ub358\ub358' MV \uacf5\uac1c \ud558\ub8e8\ub9cc 1600\ub9cc\ubdf0\u2025\ucc28\uc138\ub300 \uac78\uadf8\ub8f9 \uc138\ub300\uad50\uccb4(\uacf5\uc2dd)|publisher=HeraldPop|author=Park Seo-hyun|date=February 4, 2020|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> On April 8, 2020, the video exceeded 30 million views in two days.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.topstarnews.net/news/articleView.html?idxno=758479|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 'Oh my god', \uc774\ud2c0\ub9cc\uc5d0 MV 3,000\ub9cc\ubdf0 \ub2ec\uc131\u2026\ucd08\ub3d9 10\ub9cc\uc7a5 \ub3cc\ud30c\ub3c4...|trans-title=(G)I-dle 'Oh my god' MV reached 30 million views in two days ... exceeded 100,000 copies...|publisher=TopStarNews|author=Lee Chang-gyu|date=November 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Plagiarism accusation ===\nAfter the released of (G)I-dle's music video teaser, overseas netizens pointed out that several scenes of the \"Oh My God\" teaser video are similar in appearance and colour to British pop singer [[FKA Twigs]] released song \"[[Cellophane (FKA Twigs song)|Cellophane]]\" music video, which was released in 2019. Netizens pointed out the scene of an artist in mud or dark textured land appearing in the second half of the song. This scene represents the idea of birth or resurrection when Minnie said: \"I am no longer a prisoner\". The netizens also mentioned the scene of an artists falling among the cloths flying in the air. Lee Jin-jin of Kyunghyang Newspaper responded to the reports, stating that \"(G)I-dle's music video was filmed in a series of scenes expressing various surreal situations. On the other hand, FKA Twig's music video has a specific story of 'Crash' and 'Emergency' as the main character falls into an unknown world among pole dances, and the content and settings themselves are different.\" Soon afterwards, the controversy attracted the attention of FKA Twigs' fans causing the group's foreign fans to disproof and plunge into plagiarism claims, and continuing the arguments in overseas social networking services than domestic. A representative from Cube Entertainment responded, \"We have not yet grasped the exact situation. I'm going to find out more and resolve it.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.khan.co.kr/entertainment/sk_index.html?art_id=202004081540003&sec_id=540301&pt=nv#csidx048dcbb0b6ac054a3056441a7420164|title=[\uc2a4\uacbdX\ucd08\uc810] \ud574\uc678\uc11c \ubd88\uac70\uc9c4 (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 \u2018Oh my god\u2019 MV \ud45c\uc808 \uc758\ud639|trans-title='Excellent' (G)I-dle, Suspected plagiarism of 'Oh my god' children from overseas|publisher=Sports World|author=Lee Jin-jin|date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Promotion== \n(G)I-dle had two versions of choreography, 'black' and 'white' to be performed on music shows.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://star.mt.co.kr/stview.php?no=2020040918063517027|script-title=ko:'\uc5e0\uce74\uc6b4\ud2b8\ub2e4\uc6b4' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 \"\ucef4\ubc31 \ubb34\ub300 \uae30\ub2e4\ub824\uc8fc\uc138\uc694\" [\ubcc4\ubcc4TV]|publisher=Star News|date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> On April 9, the group performed the lead single for the first time on [[Mnet (TV channel)|Mnet]]'s ''[[M Countdown]]'' performing the black version.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.xportsnews.com/?ac=article_view&entry_id=1256803|script-title=ko:\uc5e0\uce74' \uac15\ub2e4\ub2c8\uc5d8, \ud65c\ub3d9 \uc885\ub8cc\uc5d0\ub3c4 1\uc704\u2026(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 \ud654\ub824\ud55c \ucef4\ubc31 [\uc885\ud569]|publisher=XSportsNews|date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n\"Oh My God\" debuted in the top eight major realtime music charts, including number one on three music charts, Bugs, Genie and Naver, making it their second time to top music charts since \"[[Hann (Alone)|Hann]]\" in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pop.heraldcorp.com/view.php?ud=201808160910513191755_1|title=[\ud31d\uc5c5\ubba4\uc9c1](\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 '\ud55c', \uc74c\uc6d0\ucc28\ud2b8 3\uacf3 1\uc704\u2026\uc62c\ud574\uc758 \ud56b\ub8e8\ud0a4|trans-title=[Pop-up Music] (G)I-dle 'Hann', topped 3 place in the music chart ... Hot Rookie of the Year|publisher=HeraldPop|author=Go Seung-ah|date=August 16, 2018|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title= \ud050\ube0c\uc5d4\ud130 \"(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 \uc2e0\uace1 'Oh my god' \uad6d\ub0b4 \uc74c\uc6d0 \ucc28\ud2b8 \uc11d\uad8c\"|url=https://www.mk.co.kr/news/stock/view/2020/04/362483/|website=Maeil Economy News|author=Kim Kyung-taek|date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nKarina Macias from ''[[KYLD|Wild949]]'' stated the song dives into various genres from bollywood, pop, and trap and praising the group's soft and fierce looks in the music video.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://wild949.iheart.com/content/2020-04-06-gi-dle-release-new-video-for-comeback-song-oh-my-god/?Pname=local_social&Sc=editorial&Keyid=socialflow|title=(G)I-DLE Release New Video For Comeback Song 'Oh My God'|publisher=[[KYLD|Wild949]]|author= Karina Macias |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Release history==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Region\n! Date\n! Format\n! Distributor\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Various\n| rowspan=\"2\" | April 6, 2020\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Music download|Digital download]], [[streaming media|streaming]]\n| {{hlist|[[Cube Entertainment]]|[[Kakao M]]|[[Universal Music Japan|U-Cube]]}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{(G)I-dle}}\n\n[[Category:(G)I-dle songs]]\n[[Category:2020 singles]]\n[[Category:2020 songs]]\n[[Category:Cube Entertainment singles]]\n[[Category:Korean-language songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Oh My God\n| cover      = \n| alt        = \n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[(G)I-dle]]\n| album      = [[I Trust]]\n| released   = April 6, 2020\n| format     = {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| recorded   = 2020\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[K-pop]]|[[Hip hop music|hip hop]]}}\n| length     = 3:15\n| label      = [[Cube Entertainment|Cube]]\n|writer=| producer   =  {{flatlist|\n* [[Jeon So-yeon|Soyeon]]\n* [[Cube Entertainment#In-house and guest composers|Yummy Tone]]\n* Simon Hong<ref>{{cite web|title= I Trust / (G)I-dle \u2013 TIDAL |url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/135852786/credits|publisher=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>}}\n| prev_title = [[Lion ((G)I-dle song) |Lion]]\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| next_title = \n| next_year  =\n| misc         = {{External music video\n | type        = single\n | header      = Music video\n | 1           = {{YouTube| om3n2ni8luE |\"Oh my god\"}}\n}}}}\n\n\"'''Oh My God'''\" (stylized as \"'''Oh my god'''\") is a song recorded by South Korean girl group [[(G)I-dle]] as the lead single for their third extended play ''[[I Trust]]''. It was released in Korean and English through [[Cube Entertainment|Cube]] on April 6, 2020. It was composed by [[Jeon So-yeon|Soyeon]] and long-time collaborator [[Cube Entertainment#In-house and guest composers|Yummy Tone]], while the lyrics for the English version were translated by Lauren Kaori.\n\n==Background==\n\"Oh My God\" was released in Korean and English language. According to [[Cho Mi-yeon|Miyeon]], they included the English version specially for global fans for the now-postponed ''I-Land: Who Am I Tour''.<ref name=\"celev\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theceluv.com/article.php?aid=1586162596316145007|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, '\ub2f9\ub2f9\ud568'\uc73c\ub85c 9\uac1c\uc6d4 \ub9cc\uc5d0 \ucef4\ubc31\u2026\"\ub450 \uac00\uc9c0 \ubc84\uc804 \ubb34\ub300 \uae30\ub300\"[\uc885\ud569]|work=The Celebrity News|author=Kim He-seo|date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n\"Oh My God\" was written and co-produced by leader [[Jeon So-yeon|Soyeon]], who composed the group's popular songs from \"[[Latata]]\" to \"[[Lion ((G)I-dle song) |Lion]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joynews24.com/view/1254174|title=\ucef4\ubc31' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ud0c0\uc774\ud2c0\uace1\uc740 '\uc624 \ub9c8\uc774 \uac13'\u2026'\ubbff\ub4e3' \uc804\uc18c\uc5f0 \uc790\uc791\uace1|trans-title=(G)I-dle the title song is 'Oh My God'\u2026 'Believe in' Jeon So-yeon's own composition|work=Joy News24|author= Jung Ji-won |date=March 31, 2020|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> It is composed in the key of [[E minor]], with a tempo of 110 [[beats per minute|BPM]] running 3:15 minutes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://musicstax.com/track/oh-my-god/2DmRXiyn03tOqKgEJXlaiJ|title=Key and BPM of Oh my god by (G)I-dle|website=musicstax.com|language=en-US|date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The song was conceptualized around the theme of 'self-trust' when encountering reality and experiencing feelings of rejection, confusion, recognition, and dignity. It is an urban hip hop track in which the stark differences in rhythm that correspond to the atmospheric changes within the song stand out. The fantasy-like mood and bold production are led by a vintage piano sound and strong 808 bass.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hanteonews.com/ko/article/all?fc=5227|title=[\uc2e0\ubcf4] 'I trust'\ub85c \ub3cc\uc544\uc628 (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, 'Oh my god' \uc18c\ub9ac \uc808\ub85c \ub098\uc624\ub294 \ucf58\uc149\ud2b8! \"\uc774\ubc88\uc5d0\ub3c4 \ubbff\uace0 \ub4e3\uc790!\"|trans-title=(G)I-dle returning to 'I trust', the concept of 'Oh my god' sound section! \"Let's believe and listen again!\"|work=Hanteo News|author=Kim Tae-young |date=April 3, 2020|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\"celev\"/> The song is dark, with lyrics that riff on contrasts \u2014 light and dark, purity and sin \u2014 to communicate the the idea that true divinity comes from knowing and trusting yourself.<ref name=\"mtv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3162473/gi-dle-interview-oh-my-god-soyeon-i-trust/|title=RISING STARS (G)I-DLE ARE DEFINING THEIR OWN GENRE|work=[[MTV]]|author=Crystal Bell|date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box\n |quote=\"I didn't want to limit that 'she' to a certain being or a certain definition, so it's open to anything. I believe that all kinds of love are valuable and must be respected. That's why I don't want to limit 'she' to something specific.\"\n |source = \u2014 Soyeon talking about using 'She' in \"Oh My God\".<ref name=\"mtv\"/>\n |width= 35%\n |align= right\n}}\n\nThe specific lyrics \"Oh my god / she took me to the sky / Oh my god / she showed me all the stars\" sparked listeners questioning as to whom is being referred to. Soyeon responded that the imagery and lyrics represent love in many forms, and that she will leave it to the listener to interpret it their own way.<ref name=\"mtv\"/> \n\nThe song is written in [[Point-of-view shot|third person]] because it symbolises the detachment of ones improved present self from their lackluster past self to show that they are now a better person.\n\n==Music video==\n[[File:(G)I-dle - Oh My God.png|thumbnail|(G)I-dle in \"Oh My God\" music video.]]\nBefore its release, the song was accompanied by a music video teaser released midnight [[Time in South Korea|KST]] on April 6, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hankyung.com/entertainment/article/202004068059I|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ubbf8\ub2c8 3\uc9d1 \ud0c0\uc774\ud2c0\uace1 'Oh my god' \ubba4\uc9c1\ube44\ub514\uc624 \ud2f0\uc800 \uacf5\uac1c|trans-title=(G)I-dle 3rd mini album song 'Oh my god' music video teaser released|work=Hankyung|author=Lee Jun-hyung |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> The teaser exceeded 1 million views on YouTube in 11 hours.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news1.kr/articles/?3897898|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 '\uc624 \ub9c8\uc774 \uac13' MV \ud2f0\uc800, \uacf5\uac1c 11\uc2dc\uac04 \ub9cc\uc5d0 100\ub9cc \ubdf0 \ub3cc\ud30c|trans-title=(G)I-dle 'Oh My God' MV teaser breaks 1 million views in 11 hours|work=News1|author=Kim Min-ji|date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe music video opens with a solo dance by leader Soyeon in a white room which leads her to escape the reality and gradually spread into a dream.<ref name=\"MV\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tvreport.co.kr/2037849|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \ubbff\uc74c\u2192\ub2f9\ub2f9\ud568...\ud30c\uaca9X\ubabd\ud658 'Oh my god' [\uccab\u97f3\uc0c1]|work=Tv Report|author= Park Hyun-min |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>. It contains dark visual elements such as scene that portrays confusion in ego with whole body soaked in purple liquid and red mud, black coloured body painting and pouring red liquid over ones face.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cubeent.co.kr/gidlealbum/4231703|title=(G)IDLE - I Trust album infomation|publisher=Cube Entertainment|date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> Towards the end of the video, Soojin whispers \"Ab imo pectore\" meaning 'from the bottom of my heart' or 'with deepest affection' in Latin.\n\nChoreography for the song was created by Star System while being directed by director Yoon Rima and Jang Dongju of Rigend Film production team.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.instagram.com/tv/B-ouPyMDXJW/?igshid=8bw0lb9pcpnj|title=starsystem_kor (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 [OH MY GOD] M/V|website=[[Instagram]]|date=6 April 2020}}</ref> The assistant directors were Lee Yongoh, Kim Eunah, Lee Sunhyu, Choi Eunjeong and Koo Eunji. Other key personnel were production assistant Choi Seongjin, Park Sangcheol and Il Joo while the Character Generator was Kim Eunah, Lee Sunhyu, Choi Eunjeong and Koo Eunji, Kim Bo-hyeong, Lee Yerim and Bae Haeun. The Director of Photography were Yun Inmo (ATOD), Park Junhee as the Gaffer and Shin Gwiock (A:WE) as the Art Director.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://vimeo.com/404530807|title=(G)IDLE - OH MY GOD MV|author=RIGEND FILM STUDIO|publisher=Vimeo|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA monotone lyric video for the song was released on April 8, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.donga.com/article/all/20200409/100576451/1|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \u2018Oh my god\u2019 \ub9ac\ub9ad \ube44\ub514\uc624 \uacf5\uac1c|date=April 9, 2020|publisher=Sports Donga|first=Jeon|last=Hyo-jin}}</ref>\n\n===Reception===\nMia Nazarena of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' was positive in an article about the album, praising the \"dramatic scenes with visually stunning sets, finely-tuned choreography, and carefully curated costume changes\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/9352173/g-i-dle-oh-my-god-video-i-trust-ep|title='Oh My God': (G)I-DLE Is Back With a New EP and Stunning Video|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|author=Mia Nazarena|date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 7, 2020, it was announced that the music video amassed 17 million views within 24 hours of release.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.xportsnews.com/?ac=article_view&entry_id=1255695|title=\"\ub610 \ub300\ubc15\" (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, 'Oh my god' MV 18\uc2dc\uac04\ub9cc\uc5d0 1200\ub9cc\ubdf0 \ub3cc\ud30c|trans-title=\n\"Another jackpot\" (G)I-dle, 'Oh my god' MV surpasses 12 million views in 18 hours|publisher=XSPortsNews|author=Jeon A-ram|date=April 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.g-enews.com/ko-kr/news/article/news_all/202004081105565115c4c55f9b3d_1/article.html?md=20200408112310_R#linkpop|title=[\uae00\ub85c\ubc8c-\uc5d4\ud130 24] (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, '\uc544\uc774 \ud2b8\ub7ec\uc2a4\ud2b8(I trust)' \uc544\uc774\ud2a0\uc988 \ud1b1\uc568\ubc94 35\uac1c \uc9c0\uc5ed 1\uc704|trans-title=[Global-Enter 24] (G)I-dle Ranked #1 in iTunes' Top 35 Albums of 'I Trust'|publisher=Global Economic|author=Kim Seong|date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The video broke (G)I-dle's personal record set in 2019 with the \"Lion\" music video, which garnered 5 million views in two days of its release,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportsworldi.com/newsView/20191105512364|title=\u2018\uc798 \ub098\uac00\ub294\u2019 (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4, \u2018LION' MV \u2018500\ub9cc \ubdf0 \ub3cc\ud30c\u2019|trans-title='Excellent' (G)I-dle, 'LION' MV 'Break through 5 million views'|publisher=Sports World|author=Jung Ga-young|date=November 5, 2019|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> It is also the first most viewed Kpop music videos in the first 24 hours by a girl group (fifth overall behind [[BTS]]'s \"[[Black Swan (song)|Black Swan]]\") on [[Youtube]] at that time. The record previously held by [[Everglow (group)|Everglow]]'s \"[[Reminiscence (EP)|Dun Dun]]\" with 16 million views.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pop.heraldcorp.com/view.php?ud=202002042148029652360_1|title=\uc5d0\ubc84\uae00\ub85c\uc6b0 '\ub358\ub358' MV \uacf5\uac1c \ud558\ub8e8\ub9cc 1600\ub9cc\ubdf0\u2025\ucc28\uc138\ub300 \uac78\uadf8\ub8f9 \uc138\ub300\uad50\uccb4(\uacf5\uc2dd)|publisher=HeraldPop|author=Park Seo-hyun|date=February 4, 2020|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> On April 8, 2020, the video exceeded 30 million views in two days.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.topstarnews.net/news/articleView.html?idxno=758479|title=(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 'Oh my god', \uc774\ud2c0\ub9cc\uc5d0 MV 3,000\ub9cc\ubdf0 \ub2ec\uc131\u2026\ucd08\ub3d9 10\ub9cc\uc7a5 \ub3cc\ud30c\ub3c4...|trans-title=(G)I-dle 'Oh my god' MV reached 30 million views in two days ... exceeded 100,000 copies...|publisher=TopStarNews|author=Lee Chang-gyu|date=November 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Plagiarism accusation ===\nAfter the released of (G)I-dle's music video teaser, overseas netizens pointed out that several scenes of the \"Oh My God\" teaser video are similar in appearance and colour to British pop singer [[FKA Twigs]] released song \"[[Cellophane (FKA Twigs song)|Cellophane]]\" music video, which was released in 2019. Netizens pointed out the scene of an artist in mud or dark textured land appearing in the second half of the song. This scene represents the idea of birth or resurrection when Minnie said: \"I am no longer a prisoner\". The netizens also mentioned the scene of an artists falling among the cloths flying in the air. Lee Jin-jin of Kyunghyang Newspaper responded to the reports, stating that \"(G)I-dle's music video was filmed in a series of scenes expressing various surreal situations. On the other hand, FKA Twig's music video has a specific story of 'Crash' and 'Emergency' as the main character falls into an unknown world among pole dances, and the content and settings themselves are different.\" Soon afterwards, the controversy attracted the attention of FKA Twigs' fans causing the group's foreign fans to disproof and plunge into plagiarism claims, and continuing the arguments in overseas social networking services than domestic. A representative from Cube Entertainment responded, \"We have not yet grasped the exact situation. I'm going to find out more and resolve it.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.khan.co.kr/entertainment/sk_index.html?art_id=202004081540003&sec_id=540301&pt=nv#csidx048dcbb0b6ac054a3056441a7420164|title=[\uc2a4\uacbdX\ucd08\uc810] \ud574\uc678\uc11c \ubd88\uac70\uc9c4 (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 \u2018Oh my god\u2019 MV \ud45c\uc808 \uc758\ud639|trans-title='Excellent' (G)I-dle, Suspected plagiarism of 'Oh my god' children from overseas|publisher=Sports World|author=Lee Jin-jin|date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Promotion== \n(G)I-dle had two versions of choreography, 'black' and 'white' to be performed on music shows.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://star.mt.co.kr/stview.php?no=2020040918063517027|script-title=ko:'\uc5e0\uce74\uc6b4\ud2b8\ub2e4\uc6b4' (\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 \"\ucef4\ubc31 \ubb34\ub300 \uae30\ub2e4\ub824\uc8fc\uc138\uc694\" [\ubcc4\ubcc4TV]|publisher=Star News|date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> On April 9, the group performed the lead single for the first time on [[Mnet (TV channel)|Mnet]]'s ''[[M Countdown]]'' performing the black version.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.xportsnews.com/?ac=article_view&entry_id=1256803|script-title=ko:\uc5e0\uce74' \uac15\ub2e4\ub2c8\uc5d8, \ud65c\ub3d9 \uc885\ub8cc\uc5d0\ub3c4 1\uc704\u2026(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 \ud654\ub824\ud55c \ucef4\ubc31 [\uc885\ud569]|publisher=XSportsNews|date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n\"Oh My God\" debuted in the top eight major realtime music charts, including number one on three music charts, Bugs, Genie and Naver, making it their second time to top music charts since \"[[Hann (Alone)|Hann]]\" in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pop.heraldcorp.com/view.php?ud=201808160910513191755_1|title=[\ud31d\uc5c5\ubba4\uc9c1](\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 '\ud55c', \uc74c\uc6d0\ucc28\ud2b8 3\uacf3 1\uc704\u2026\uc62c\ud574\uc758 \ud56b\ub8e8\ud0a4|trans-title=[Pop-up Music] (G)I-dle 'Hann', topped 3 place in the music chart ... Hot Rookie of the Year|publisher=HeraldPop|author=Go Seung-ah|date=August 16, 2018|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title= \ud050\ube0c\uc5d4\ud130 \"(\uc5ec\uc790)\uc544\uc774\ub4e4 \uc2e0\uace1 'Oh my god' \uad6d\ub0b4 \uc74c\uc6d0 \ucc28\ud2b8 \uc11d\uad8c\"|url=https://www.mk.co.kr/news/stock/view/2020/04/362483/|website=Maeil Economy News|author=Kim Kyung-taek|date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nKarina Macias from ''[[KYLD|Wild949]]'' stated the song dives into various genres from bollywood, pop, and trap and praising the group's soft and fierce looks in the music video.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://wild949.iheart.com/content/2020-04-06-gi-dle-release-new-video-for-comeback-song-oh-my-god/?Pname=local_social&Sc=editorial&Keyid=socialflow|title=(G)I-DLE Release New Video For Comeback Song 'Oh My God'|publisher=[[KYLD|Wild949]]|author= Karina Macias |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Release history==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Region\n! Date\n! Format\n! Distributor\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Various\n| rowspan=\"2\" | April 6, 2020\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Music download|Digital download]], [[streaming media|streaming]]\n| {{hlist|[[Cube Entertainment]]|[[Kakao M]]|[[Universal Music Japan|U-Cube]]}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{(G)I-dle}}\n\n[[Category:(G)I-dle songs]]\n[[Category:2020 singles]]\n[[Category:2020 songs]]\n[[Category:Cube Entertainment singles]]\n[[Category:Korean-language songs]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oh_My_God_((G)I-dle_song)"}
{"title_page": "Vasyl Novokhatsky", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Vasyl Novokhatskyi\n| image = \n| fullname = Vasyl Novokhatskyi\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1974|4|29|df=yes}}\n| birth_place =[[Kalynivka, Vinnytsia Oblast]], [[Soviet Union]]\n| height = {{height|m=1.90}}\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| position = Midfielder\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1992 | clubs1 = [[PFC Nyva Vinnytsia|Nyva Vinnytsia]] | caps1 = 8 | goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 1993\u20131994 | clubs2 = [[FC CSKA Kyiv|CSKA Kyiv]] | caps2 = 52 | goals2 = 9\n| years3 = 1995 | clubs3 = [[FC Arsenal Kyiv|CSKA-Borysfen Kyiv]] | caps3 = 11 | goals3 = 3\n| years4 = 1995\u20131996 | clubs4 = [[Ionikos F.C.|Ionikos]] | caps4 = 31 | goals4 = 10\n| years5 = 1996\u20131997 | clubs5 = [[Maccabi Haifa F.C.|Maccabi Haifa]] | caps5 = 9 | goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 1997\u20131998 | clubs6 = [[Panachaiki]] | caps6 = 25 | goals6 = 4\n| years7 = 1998\u20131999 | clubs7 = [[FC Arsenal Kyiv|CSKA Kyiv]] | caps7 = 7 | goals7 = 0\n| years8 = 1998\u20131999 | clubs8 = \u2192 [[FC CSKA Kyiv|CSKA-2 Kyiv]] ''(loan)''| caps8 = 15 | goals8 = 1\n| years9 = 2001\u20132002 | clubs9 = [[Chania F.C.|Chania]] | caps9 = | goals9 = \n| years10= 2010\u20132011 | clubs10= SC Kalynivka | caps10= 11 | goals10= 1\n| nationalyears1 = | nationalteam1 = | nationalcaps1 = | nationalgoals1 = \n| manageryears1 = | managerclubs1 =  \n| pcupdate = \n| ntupdate =\n}}\n'''Vasyl Novokhatskyi''' ({{lang-ua|\u0412\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043b\u044c \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0445\u0430\u0446\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439}}; born 24 september 1974) is a retired [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Midfielder (association football)|midfielder]] for clubs in Ukraine, Greece, and Israel. His last name often is misspelled as Novohatsky ({{lang-ua|\u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0433\u0430\u0446\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439}}), because of a [[transliteration]] inconsistency.\n\n==Club career==\nNovokhatskyi began playing football for [[Ukrainian Premier League]] side [[PFC Nyva Vinnytsia]]. Soon, he joined [[FC CSKA Kyiv]], and would score a goal as the club lost the [[1997\u201398 Ukrainian Cup]] final.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=\"Den\"|script-title=uk:\u0413\u0456\u0434\u043d\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u043c'\u0454\u0440\u0430 \u0426\u0421\u041a\u0410 \u0432 \u0434\u0435\u043d\u044c \u0442\u0440\u0435\u0442\u044c\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0437\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0443 \u0414\u0438\u043d\u0430\u043c\u043e|author1=Marusenko, Petro  |author2=Karelskyi, Evhen |lastauthoramp=yes |url=http://www.day.kiev.ua/142222/|language=Ukrainian|date=2 June 1998}}</ref>\n\nIn July 1995, Novokhatskyi joined [[Greek Superleague]] side [[Ionikos F.C.]] for the one season. He spent the following season with [[Maccabi Haifa F.C.]] before returning to Greece to play for [[Panachaiki|Panachaiki F.C.]] for one season.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[RSSSF]]|author=Mastrogiannopoulos, Alexander|title=Foreign Players in Greece since 1959/60|url=http://www.rsssf.com/players/foreign-players-in-grk6080.html|date=11 May 2005}}</ref>\n\nHe played for [[Gamma Ethniki|Greek third division]] side [[Chania F.C.]] during the 2001\u201302 season.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=epae.org|title=\u03a0\u03c1\u03c9\u03c4\u03ac\u03b8\u03bb\u03b7\u03bc\u03b1 / FOOTBALL LEAGUE 2 / \u03a0\u03a1\u03a9\u03a4\u0391\u0398\u039b\u0397\u039c\u0391 \u0393 ' \u0395\u0398\u039d\u0399\u039a\u0397\u03a3 \u039a\u0391\u03a4\u0397\u0393\u039f\u03a1\u0399\u0391\u03a3 2001-2002 / 1\u03b7 \u03b1\u03b3\u03c9\u03bd\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae / \u039c\u0391\u03a1\u039a\u039f \u039c\u0391\u03a1\u039a\u039f\u03a0\u039f\u03a5\u039b\u039f\u03a5 \u0393\u03a3 \u03a0\u0391\u0395 - \u03a7\u0391\u039d\u0399\u0391 \u0391.\u039f. \u03a0\u0391\u0395|url=http://www.epae.org/match.fds?categ=3&dior_code=53&cal_day=1&game=3&group=0&type=1&pagecode=01.03&langid=1|language=Greek|date=3 October 2001}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{FFU Profile|25852}}\n*[http://legioner.kulichki.com/index.php?id=11&lang=en&player=312 Profile at legioner.kulichki.com]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110724033111/http://www.axaioi3.gr/forum/index.php?topic=133.0 \u039e\u0395\u039d\u039f\u0399 \u03a0\u0391\u0399\u039a\u03a4\u0395\u03a3 \u039a\u0391\u0399 \u03a0\u03a1\u039f\u03a0\u039f\u039d\u0397\u03a4\u0395\u03a3 \u03a4\u0397\u03a3 \u03a0\u0391\u039d\u0391\u03a7\u0391\u03aa\u039a\u0397\u03a3]\n\n{{use dmy dates|date=September 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Novokhatskyi, Vasyl}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Kalynivka]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian footballers]]\n[[Category:FC Nyva Vinnytsia players]]\n[[Category:FC Dnipro Cherkasy players]]\n[[Category:FC CSKA Kyiv players]]\n[[Category:FC Arsenal Kyiv players]]\n[[Category:Ionikos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Panachaiki F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Maccabi Haifa F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian military personnel of the War in Donbass]]\n\n\n{{Ukraine-footy-midfielder-1970s-stub}}\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Vasyl Novokhatskyi\n| image = \n| fullname = Vasyl Novokhatskyi\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1974|4|29|df=yes}}\n| birth_place =[[Kalynivka, Vinnytsia Oblast]], [[Soviet Union]]\n| height = {{height|m=1.90}}\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| position = Midfielder\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1992 | clubs1 = [[PFC Nyva Vinnytsia|Nyva Vinnytsia]] | caps1 = 8 | goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 1993\u20131994 | clubs2 = [[FC CSKA Kyiv|CSKA Kyiv]] | caps2 = 52 | goals2 = 9\n| years3 = 1995 | clubs3 = [[FC Arsenal Kyiv|CSKA-Borysfen Kyiv]] | caps3 = 11 | goals3 = 3\n| years4 = 1995\u20131996 | clubs4 = [[Ionikos F.C.|Ionikos]] | caps4 = 31 | goals4 = 10\n| years5 = 1996\u20131997 | clubs5 = [[Maccabi Haifa F.C.|Maccabi Haifa]] | caps5 = 9 | goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 1997\u20131998 | clubs6 = [[Panachaiki]] | caps6 = 25 | goals6 = 4\n| years7 = 1998\