3=Ivan |last94=Valentin |first94=Fr\u00e9d\u00e9rique |last95=Vasilyev |first95=Sergey |last96=Veljanovska |first96=Fanica |last97=Venelinova |first97=Svetlana |last98=Veselovskaya |first98=Elizaveta |last99=Viola |first99=Bence |last100=Virag |first100=Cristian |last101=Zaninovi\u0107 |first101=Jo\u0161ko |last102=Z\u00e4uner |first102=Steve |last103=Stockhammer |first103=Philipp W. |last104=Catalano |first104=Giulio |last105=Krau\u00df |first105=Raiko |last106=Caramelli |first106=David |last107=Zari\u0146a |first107=Gunita |last108=Gaydarska |first108=Bisserka |last109=Lillie |first109=Malcolm |last110=Nikitin |first110=Alexey G. |last111=Potekhina |first111=Inna |last112=Papathanasiou |first112=Anastasia |last113=Bori\u0107 |first113=Du\u0161an |last114=Bonsall |first114=Clive |last115=Krause |first115=Johannes |last116=Pinhasi |first116=Ron |last117=Reich |first117=David |title=The genomic history of southeastern Europe |journal=Nature |date=21 February 2018 |volume=555 |issue=7695 |pages=197\u2013203 |doi=10.1038/nature25778 |pmid=29466330 |pmc=6091220 |url=http://real.mtak.hu/63901/1/135616.full.pdf }}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Mathieson |first1=Iain |author-link1= |date=November 23, 2015 |editor1-last= |editor1-first= |editor1-link= |title=Genome-wide patterns of selection in 230 ancient Eurasians |script-title= |trans-title= |department= |journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]] |type= |series= |language= |edition= |publisher=[[Nature Research]] |publication-date= |volume=528 |issue=7583 |pages=499\u2013503 |nopp= |arxiv= |asin= |bibcode= |bibcode-access= |biorxiv= |citeseerx= |doi=10.1038/nature16152 |doi-access= |issn= |jfm= |jstor= |jstor-access= |lccn= |mr= |oclc= |ol= |ol-access= |osti= |osti-access= |pmc=4918750 |pmid=26595274 |rfc= |ssrn= |zbl= |id= |layurl= |laysource= |laydate= |quote= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Mittnik |first1=Alisa |author-link1= |date=January 30, 2018 |editor1-last= |editor1-first= |editor1-link= |title=The genetic prehistory of the Baltic Sea region |script-title= |trans-title= |department= |journal=[[Nature Communications]] |type= |series= |language= |edition= |publisher=[[Nature Research]] |publication-date= |volume=16 |issue=1 |pages= 442|nopp= |arxiv= |asin= |bibcode= |bibcode-access= |biorxiv= |citeseerx=  |doi=10.1038/s41467-018-02825-9 |doi-access= |issn= |jfm= |jstor= |jstor-access= |lccn= |mr= |oclc= |ol= |ol-access= |osti= |osti-access= |pmc=5789860 |pmid=29382937 |rfc= |ssrn= |zbl= |id= |layurl= |laysource= |laydate= |quote= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Narasimhan |first1=Vagheesh M. |author-link1= |date=September 6, 2019 |editor1-last= |editor1-first= |editor1-link= |title=The formation of human populations in South and Central Asia |script-title= |trans-title= |department= |journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]] |type= |series= |language= |edition= |publisher=[[American Association for the Advancement of Science]] |publication-date= |volume=365 |issue=6457 |page= eaat7487 |nopp= |arxiv= |asin= |bibcode= |bibcode-access= |biorxiv=292581 |citeseerx= |doi=10.1126/science.aat7487 |doi-access= |issn= |jfm= |jstor= |jstor-access= |lccn= |mr= |oclc= |ol= |ol-access= |osti= |osti-access= |pmc= 6822619|pmid= 31488661|rfc= |ssrn= |zbl= |id= |layurl= |laysource= |laydate= |quote= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |ref=harv |display-authors=3 |last1=Raghavan |first1=Maanasa |last2=Skoglund |first2=Pontus |last3=Graf |first3=Kelly E. |last4=Metspalu |first4=Mait |last5=Albrechtsen |first5=Anders |last6=Moltke |first6=Ida |last7=Rasmussen |first7=Simon |last8=Stafford Jr |first8=Thomas W. |last9=Orlando |first9=Ludovic |last10=Metspalu |first10=Ene |last11=Karmin |first11=Monika |last12=Tambets |first12=Kristiina |last13=Rootsi |first13=Siiri |last14=M\u00e4gi |first14=Reedik |last15=Campos |first15=Paula F. |last16=Balanovska |first16=Elena |last17=Balanovsky |first17=Oleg |last18=Khusnutdinova |first18=Elza |last19=Litvinov |first19=Sergey |last20=Osipova |first20=Ludmila P. |last21=Fedorova |first21=Sardana A. |last22=Voevoda |first22=Mikhail I. |last23=DeGiorgio |first23=Michael |last24=Sicheritz-Ponten |first24=Thomas |last25=Brunak |first25=S\u00f8ren |last26=Demeshchenko |first26=Svetlana |last27=Kivisild |first27=Toomas |last28=Villems |first28=Richard |last29=Nielsen |first29=Rasmus |last30=Jakobsson |first30=Mattias |last31=Willerslev |first31=Eske |title=Upper Palaeolithic Siberian genome reveals dual ancestry of Native Americans |journal=Nature |date=20 November 2013 |volume=505 |issue=7481 |pages=87\u201391 |doi=10.1038/nature12736 |pmid=24256729 |pmc=4105016 |bibcode=2014Natur.505...87R }}\n* {{cite journal |ref=harv |display-authors=3 |last1=Lazaridis |first2=Anna |last2=Belfer-Cohen |first3=Swapan |last3=Mallick |first4=Nick |last4=Patterson |first5=Olivia |last5=Cheronet |first6=Nadin |last6=Rohland |first7=Guy |last7=Bar-Oz |first8=Ofer |last8=Bar-Yosef |first9=Nino |last9=Jakeli |first10=Eliso |last10=Kvavadze |first11=David |last11=Lordkipanidze |first12=Zinovi |last12=Matzkevich |first13=Tengiz |last13=Meshveliani |first14=Brendan J. |last14=Culleton |first15=Douglas J. |last15=Kennett |first16=Ron |last16=Pinhasi |first17=David |last17=Reich |year=2018 |title=Paleolithic DNA from the Caucasus reveals core of West Eurasian ancestry |journal=[[bioRxiv]] |doi=10.1101/423079 }}\n\n[[Category:Archaeogenetic lineages|ANE]]\n[[Category:Genetic history of Europe]]\n[[Category:Peopling of the world]]\n[[Category:Peopling of the Americas]]\n[[Category:Indo-European genetics]]\n[[Category:Last Glacial Maximum]]\n[[Category:Mesolithic]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Archaeogenetic name for an ancestral genetic component}}\n[[File:Sunghir Man.png|thumb|[[Gravettian]]s are ancestral to all West Eurasian populations. ANE derive most of their ancestry from a population closely related to the remains from [[Sungir]], such as the man from this reconstruction.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}]]\nIn [[archaeogenetics]], the term '''Ancient North Eurasian''' (ANE) is the name given to an ancestral component that represents descent from the people similar to the [[Mal'ta\u2013Buret' culture]] or a population [[Afontova Gora|closely related]] to them.{{sfn|Flegontov|Changmai|Zidkova|Logacheva|2016}}\n\n==Genetic studies==\nThe ANE lineage is defined by association with MA-1, or \"[[Mal'ta boy]]\", the remains of an individual who lived during the [[Last Glacial Maximum]], 24,000 years ago, discovered in the 1920s.\nPopulations genetically similar to MA-1 were an important genetic contributor to [[Genetic history of indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native Americans]], [[genetic history of Europe|Europeans]], [[Genetic history of Central Asia|Central Asians]], [[genetic history of South Asia|South Asians]], and some [[Mongoloid|East Asians]], in order of significance.{{sfn|Lazaridis|Nadel|Rollefson|Merrett|2016}}\nLazaridis et al. (2016:10) note \"a cline of ANE ancestry across the east-west extent of Eurasia.\"{{sfn|Lazaridis|Nadel|Rollefson|Merrett|2016}} Flegontov et al. (2016) found that the global maximum of ANE ancestry occurs in modern-day  [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native Americans]], [[Ket people|Kets]] and [[Selkup people|Selkup]].{{sfn|Flegontov|Changmai|Zidkova|Logacheva|2016}}\nAdditionally it has been reported in ancient Bronze-age-steppe [[Yamna culture|Yamnaya]] and [[Afanasevo culture|Afanasevo]] cultures.{{sfn|Haak|Lazaridis|Patterson|Rohland|2015}} 42% of South American Native American ancestry originates from ANE peoples,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wong |first1=Emily H.M. |last2=Khrunin |first2=Andrey |last3=Nichols |first3=Larissa |last4=Pushkarev |first4=Dmitry |last5=Khokhrin |first5=Denis |last6=Verbenko |first6=Dmitry |last7=Evgrafov |first7=Oleg |last8=Knowles |first8=James |last9=Novembre |first9=John |last10=Limborska |first10=Svetlana |last11=Valouev |first11=Anton |title=Reconstructing genetic history of Siberian and Northeastern European populations |journal=Genome Research |date=January 2017 |volume=27 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201314 |doi=10.1101/gr.202945.115 |pmid=27965293 |pmc=5204334 }}</ref> while between 14% and 38% of North American Native American ancestry may originate from gene flow from the Mal'ta Buret people. This difference is caused by the penetration of posterior Siberian migrations into the Americas, with the lowest percentages of ANE ancestry found in Eskimos and Alaskan Natives, as these groups are the result of migrations into the Americas roughly 5,000 years ago.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Moreno-Mayar |first1=J. V\u00edctor |last2=Vinner |first2=Lasse |last3=de Barros Damgaard |first3=Peter |last4=de la Fuente |first4=Constanza |last5=Chan |first5=Jeffrey |last6=Spence |first6=Jeffrey P. |last7=Allentoft |first7=Morten E. |last8=Vimala |first8=Tharsika |last9=Racimo |first9=Fernando |last10=Pinotti |first10=Thomaz |last11=Rasmussen |first11=Simon |last12=Margaryan |first12=Ashot |last13=Iraeta Orbegozo |first13=Miren |last14=Mylopotamitaki |first14=Dorothea |last15=Wooller |first15=Matthew |last16=Bataille |first16=Clement |last17=Becerra-Valdivia |first17=Lorena |last18=Chivall |first18=David |last19=Comeskey |first19=Daniel |last20=Devi\u00e8se |first20=Thibaut |last21=Grayson |first21=Donald K. |last22=George |first22=Len |last23=Harry |first23=Harold |last24=Alexandersen |first24=Verner |last25=Primeau |first25=Charlotte |last26=Erlandson |first26=Jon |last27=Rodrigues-Carvalho |first27=Claudia |last28=Reis |first28=Silvia |last29=Bastos |first29=Murilo Q. R. |last30=Cybulski |first30=Jerome |last31=Vullo |first31=Carlos |last32=Morello |first32=Flavia |last33=Vilar |first33=Miguel |last34=Wells |first34=Spencer |last35=Gregersen |first35=Kristian |last36=Hansen |first36=Kasper Lykke |last37=Lynnerup |first37=Niels |last38=Miraz\u00f3n Lahr |first38=Marta |last39=Kj\u00e6r |first39=Kurt |last40=Strauss |first40=Andr\u00e9 |last41=Alfonso-Durruty |first41=Marta |last42=Salas |first42=Antonio |last43=Schroeder |first43=Hannes |last44=Higham |first44=Thomas |last45=Malhi |first45=Ripan S. |last46=Rasic |first46=Jeffrey T. |last47=Souza |first47=Luiz |last48=Santos |first48=Fabricio R. |last49=Malaspinas |first49=Anna-Sapfo |last50=Sikora |first50=Martin |last51=Nielsen |first51=Rasmus |last52=Song |first52=Yun S. |last53=Meltzer |first53=David J. |last54=Willerslev |first54=Eske |title=Early human dispersals within the Americas |journal=Science |date=7 December 2018 |volume=362 |issue=6419 |pages=eaav2621 |doi=10.1126/science.aav2621 |pmid=30409807 }}</ref> The other gene flow in Native Americans appears to have an [[Eastern Eurasia]]n origin.{{sfn|Raghavan|Skoglund|Graf|Metspalu|2013}} Gene sequencing of another south-central Siberian [[Afontova Gora|people (Afontova Gora-2]]) dating to approximately 17,000 years ago, revealed similar autosomal genetic signatures to that of Mal'ta boy-1, suggesting that the region was continuously occupied by humans throughout the Last Glacial Maximum.{{sfn|Raghavan|Skoglund|Graf|Metspalu|2013}}\n\nGenomic studies also indicate that ANE was introduced to Western Europe by way of the [[Yamna culture|Yamna/Yamnaya culture]], long after the Paleolithic.{{sfn|Haak|Lazaridis|Patterson|Rohland|2015}}{{sfn|Flegontov|Changmai|Zidkova|Logacheva|2016}} The ANE genetic component is visible in tests of the [[Yamna culture|Yamnaya]] people, and seems to make up 50% of their ancestry indirectly.{{sfn|Haak|Lazaridis|Patterson|Rohland|2015}}{{sfn|Flegontov|Changmai|Zidkova|Logacheva|2016}} It is also reported in modern-day Europeans (7%\u201325% ANE admixture directly from Yamnaya), but not of Europeans predating the Bronze Age.{{sfn|Haak|Lazaridis|Patterson|Rohland|2015}}{{sfn|Flegontov|Changmai|Zidkova|Logacheva|2016}} Additional ANE ancestry is found in European populations through paleolithic interactions with Eastern Hunter-Gatherers, which resulted in populations such as Scandinavian Hunter-Gatherers.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=G\u00fcnther |first1=Torsten |last2=Malmstr\u00f6m |first2=Helena |last3=Svensson |first3=Emma M. |last4=Omrak |first4=Ay\u00e7a |last5=S\u00e1nchez-Quinto |first5=Federico |last6=K\u0131l\u0131n\u00e7 |first6=G\u00fcl\u015fah M. |last7=Krzewi\u0144ska |first7=Maja |last8=Eriksson |first8=Gunilla |last9=Fraser |first9=Magdalena |last10=Edlund |first10=Hanna |last11=Munters |first11=Arielle R. |last12=Coutinho |first12=Alexandra |last13=Sim\u00f5es |first13=Luciana G. |last14=Vicente |first14=M\u00e1rio |last15=Sj\u00f6lander |first15=Anders |last16=Jansen Sellevold |first16=Berit |last17=J\u00f8rgensen |first17=Roger |last18=Claes |first18=Peter |last19=Shriver |first19=Mark D. |last20=Valdiosera |first20=Cristina |last21=Netea |first21=Mihai G. |last22=Apel |first22=Jan |last23=Lid\u00e9n |first23=Kerstin |last24=Skar |first24=Birgitte |last25=Stor\u00e5 |first25=Jan |last26=G\u00f6therstr\u00f6m |first26=Anders |last27=Jakobsson |first27=Mattias |last28=Barton |first28=Nick |title=Population genomics of Mesolithic Scandinavia: Investigating early postglacial migration routes and high-latitude adaptation |journal=PLOS Biology |date=9 January 2018 |volume=16 |issue=1 |pages=e2003703 |doi=10.1371/journal.pbio.2003703 |pmid=29315301 |pmc=5760011 }}</ref>\n\n==Groups derived from the Ancient North Eurasians==\n{{anchor|EHG}}\n'''[[Eastern European Hunter-Gatherer]]''' (EHG) is a lineage derived predominantly (75%) from ANE.{{sfn|Lazaridis|Nadel|Rollefson|Merrett|2016}} It is represented by two individuals from [[Karelia]], one of Y-haplogroup R1a-M417, dated c. 8.4 kya, the other of Y-haplogroup J, dated c. 7.2 kya; and one individual from [[Samara]], of Y-haplogroup R1b-P297, dated c. 7.6 kya. This lineage is closely related to the ANE sample from [[Afontova Gora]], dated c. 18 kya.\nAfter the end of the Last Glacial Maximum, the [[Western Hunter-Gatherer]]s (WHG) and EHG lineages merged in Eastern Europe, accounting for early presence of ANE-derived ancestry in Mesolithic Europe. Evidence suggests that as Ancient North Eurasians migrated West from Eastern Siberia, they absorbed Western Hunter-Gatherers and other West Eurasian populations as well.{{sfn|Mathieson|Alpaslan-Roodenberg|Posth|Sz\u00e9cs\u00e9nyi-Nagy|2018}}\n\n'''[[Caucasian Hunter-Gatherer]]''' (CHG) is represented by the Satsurblia individual dated ~13 kya (from the [[Satsurblia Cave|Satsurblia cave]] in [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]), and carried 36% ANE-derived admixture.{{sfn|Lazaridis|Belfer-Cohen|Mallick|Patterson|2018}} While the rest of their ancestry is derived from the Dzudzuana cave individual dated ~26 kya, which lacked ANE-admixture,{{sfn|Lazaridis|Belfer-Cohen|Mallick|Patterson|2018}} Dzudzuana affinity in the Caucasus decreased with the arrival of ANE at ~13 kya Satsurblia.{{sfn|Lazaridis|Belfer-Cohen|Mallick|Patterson|2018}}\n\n'''[[Scandinavian Hunter-Gatherer]]''' (SHG) is represented by several individuals buried at [[Motala]], Sweden ca. 6000 BC. They were descended from [[Western Hunter-Gatherer]]s who initially settled [[Scandinavia]] from the south, and later populations of EHG who entered Scandinavia from the north through the coast of [[Norway]].{{sfn|Laziridis|2014}}{{sfn|Haak|Lazaridis|Patterson|Rohland|2015}}{{sfn|Mathieson|2015}}{{sfn|G\u00fcnther|2018}}{{sfn|Mittnik|2018}}\n\n'''Iran Neolithic''' (Iran_N) individuals dated ~8.5 kya carried 50% ANE-derived admixture and 50% Dzudzuana-related admixture,{{sfn|Lazaridis|Belfer-Cohen|Mallick|Patterson|2018}} marking them as different from other Near-Eastern and Anatolian Neolithics who didn't have ANE admixture.{{sfn|Lazaridis|Belfer-Cohen|Mallick|Patterson|2018}} Iran Neolithics were later replaced by Iran Chalcolithics, who were a mixture of Iran Neolithic and Near Eastern Levant Neolithic.{{sfn|Lazaridis|Nadel|Rollefson|Merrett|2016}}\n\n'''[[Ancient Beringian|Ancient Beringian/Ancestral Native American]]''' are specific archaeogenetic lineages, based on the genome of an infant found at the Upward Sun River site (dubbed USR1), dated to 11,500 years ago.<ref name=\"Moreno-Mayar2018\">{{cite journal |last1=Moreno-Mayar |first1=J. V\u00edctor |last2=Potter |first2=Ben A. |last3=Vinner |first3=Lasse |last4=Steinr\u00fccken |first4=Matthias |last5=Rasmussen |first5=Simon |last6=Terhorst |first6=Jonathan |last7=Kamm |first7=John A. |last8=Albrechtsen |first8=Anders |last9=Malaspinas |first9=Anna-Sapfo |last10=Sikora |first10=Martin |last11=Reuther |first11=Joshua D. |last12=Irish |first12=Joel D. |last13=Malhi |first13=Ripan S. |last14=Orlando |first14=Ludovic |last15=Song |first15=Yun S. |last16=Nielsen |first16=Rasmus |last17=Meltzer |first17=David J. |last18=Willerslev |first18=Eske |title=Terminal Pleistocene Alaskan genome reveals first founding population of Native Americans |journal=Nature |date=January 2018 |volume=553 |issue=7687 |pages=203\u2013207 |doi=10.1038/nature25173 |pmid=29323294 |url=http://researchonline.ljmu.ac.uk/id/eprint/7887/1/UpwardSun_Nature%20paper%20MS%20DEC17.pdf }}</ref> The AB lineage diverged from the Ancestral Native American (ANA) lineage about 20,000 years ago. The ANA lineage was estimated as been formed 20,000 ago by a mixture of  and Ancient North Eurasian (42-43%) and [[Eastern Eurasia|East Eurasian]] (57-58%) lineage consistent with the model of the peopling of the Americas via Beringia during the Last Glacial Maximum.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wong |first1=Emily H.M. |last2=Khrunin |first2=Andrey |last3=Nichols |first3=Larissa |last4=Pushkarev |first4=Dmitry |last5=Khokhrin |first5=Denis |last6=Verbenko |first6=Dmitry |last7=Evgrafov |first7=Oleg |last8=Knowles |first8=James |last9=Novembre |first9=John |last10=Limborska |first10=Svetlana |last11=Valouev |first11=Anton |title=Reconstructing genetic history of Siberian and Northeastern European populations |journal=Genome Research |date=January 2017 |volume=27 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201314 |doi=10.1101/gr.202945.115 |pmid=27965293 |pmc=5204334 }}</ref>\n\n'''[[West Siberian Hunter-Gatherer]]''' (WSG) are a specific archaeogenetic lineage, first reported in a genetic study published in [[Science (journal)|Science]] in September 2019. WSGs were found to be of about 30% EHG ancestry, 50% ANE ancestry, and 20% East Asian ancestry.{{sfn|Narasimhan|2019}}\n\n==Evolution of blond hair==\nThe derived allele of the [[KITLG]] SNP rs12821256 is associated with, and likely causal for, blond hair in Europeans.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Guenther |first1=Catherine A |last2=Tasic |first2=Bosiljka |last3=Luo |first3=Liqun |last4=Bedell |first4=Mary A |last5=Kingsley |first5=David M |title=A molecular basis for classic blond hair color in Europeans |journal=Nature Genetics |date=1 June 2014 |volume=46 |issue=7 |pages=748\u2013752 |doi=10.1038/ng.2991 |pmid=24880339 |pmc=4704868 }}</ref> The earliest known individual with this allele is the Siberian ANE individual Afontova Gora 3, which is dated to 16130-15749 BCE.{{sfn|Mathieson|Alpaslan-Roodenberg|Posth|Sz\u00e9cs\u00e9nyi-Nagy|2018}} This allele is also present in one hunter-gatherer from each of Samara, Motala and Ukraine (I0124, I0014 and I1763), as well as several later individuals with [[Steppe ancestry]]. Since the allele is found in populations with EHG but not [[Western Hunter-Gatherer]] ancestry, it suggests that its origin is in the Ancient North Eurasian population.\n\nGeneticist [[David Reich_(geneticist)|David Reich]] said that the the [[KITLG]] gene for blond hair entered continental Europe in a massive population migration from the Eurasian steppe, by a people who had Ancient North Eurasian ancestry.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Reich |first1=David |title=Who We are and How We Got Here: Ancient DNA and the New Science of the Human Past |date=2018 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=0198821255 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uLNSDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA96}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Western Hunter-Gatherer]]\n* [[Caucasian Hunter-Gatherer]]\n\n==References==\